00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:43.450
with members of these teams.

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:47.280
So the story of
curriculum mapping.

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:51.916
Overheard in the yard in 2016.

00:03:51.916 --> 00:03:53.790
I don't even know why
it was required to take

00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:54.900
a course before this one.

00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:56.382
It didn't really
help prepare me.

00:03:56.382 --> 00:03:57.840
I asked the professor,
and he said,

00:03:57.840 --> 00:03:59.048
he didn't really know either.

00:03:59.048 --> 00:04:01.470
He said, he was told it should
be listed as a pre-req when

00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:04.708
he started here and was asked to
take over teaching the course.

00:04:04.708 --> 00:04:07.030
[LAUGHING]

00:04:07.030 --> 00:04:11.440
So this is slightly outside
of the yard, where I heard it.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:13.740
And this is a paraphrase.

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:16.680
I didn't actually
take the quote down.

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:19.950
But the three parts
of this I overheard,

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:23.130
which was a student
saying he didn't

00:04:23.130 --> 00:04:25.080
understand why he was
having to take something

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:28.620
as a prerequisite.

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:30.990
And saying that the
professor didn't know either.

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.330
And then the inherited
part that the professor

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:35.040
inherited the course.

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:36.760
And so all of these
things, I think,

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:41.220
are related to how
a curriculum evolves

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:43.200
and how it begins
to-- it may have

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:47.760
started with an intentional
plan, within a department, say.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:50.640
And then it evolves over time
in a way that it's lost--

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:52.710
we've lost the thread,
so that students

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:55.640
and faculty and decision
makers who are administrators

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:57.840
in the department
no longer know why

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:01.100
these sequences go together,
why courses go together.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.510
And we certainly don't
have an insight, often,

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:07.120
into the kinds of things
that are being taught

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:08.530
in someone else's
course that may

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:12.280
have a title even very similar
to the one that we're teaching.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:18.220
Hearing this and
similar kinds of things,

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.920
I became more
attuned to the work

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:23.380
that other people were
doing that seemed like it

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:25.110
was addressing this kind of--

00:05:25.110 --> 00:05:26.740
a set of problems.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:28.810
And then I was at
a reception at MIT.

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:31.870
And I met a faculty
member there named

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:35.680
Karen Willcox who is a professor
of aeronautical engineering.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:38.200
And she was working with
a bunch of MIT students

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:42.760
to really carefully
map their curriculum.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:44.590
So that got me super excited.

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:49.840
And we brought Karen over for
a speaker series, was it--

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:51.850
three speaker series ago.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.140
And I thought this
is our solution.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:56.860
Karen's architecture and
what she's working on,

00:05:56.860 --> 00:05:59.410
we can just import it here.

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:00.580
And so we tried to do that.

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:02.680
And it didn't work,
because we're Harvard.

00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:04.030
And we're not like MIT.

00:06:04.030 --> 00:06:05.920
And I should have known that.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:07.790
Of course, I do know that.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:09.490
But we instead, I
think, have to do it

00:06:09.490 --> 00:06:12.010
a different way,
which is to identify

00:06:12.010 --> 00:06:15.580
all of the different kinds of
curricular mapping exercises,

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:18.640
and then think about
how do they individually

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:21.580
sum up to something that
we can take and think

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:27.710
about systematic ways of making
the curriculum more visible.

00:06:27.710 --> 00:06:30.310
So part of what we
were doing initially

00:06:30.310 --> 00:06:34.030
was having a small working
group that got together.

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:36.550
And then the working
group began to expand.

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:42.520
And it has continued to expand,
and players in this picture

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:47.080
have come in and out,
and there are probably

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:50.950
slots there that we could
put different faces.

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:52.720
And then at different
times when we've

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:56.530
tried to explain how these
curriculum mapping projects

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:59.620
may or may not go together--

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:01.480
I've bucketed them.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:03.940
And these are two buckets--

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:07.060
ways that we've
tried to bucket them.

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.820
It's imperfect, but we're
going to try to follow along

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:13.610
a little bit as a way to give
a structure to all of these 10

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:14.110
projects.

00:07:14.110 --> 00:07:16.840
So projects addressing
content that's

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:18.940
taught across Harvard
schools and projects

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:21.220
addressing student
learning and enrollment

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:24.670
patterns within subjects is the
way we're talking about this.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:30.940
So we have this
working group and then

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:36.370
we have an organization that
holds many organizations

00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:38.860
in the Office of the
President and Provost.

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:41.350
And our role, within
the Vice Provost

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:45.370
for Advances in
Learning umbrella

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:48.100
is to try to help
the schools who

00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:51.010
are working on their own
teaching and learning efforts.

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:52.660
And we do so in
different ways in

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:54.940
these different organizations.

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:58.797
So HILT, our role--

00:07:58.797 --> 00:08:00.880
I'll say a little bit more
about HILT in a minute,

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:05.500
but we primarily do grant
making and convening.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:12.250
And HarvardX, as you know, is
really an amazing organization

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:17.320
for experimentation in
curriculum design, pedagogy,

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:19.930
and even understanding new
ways that courses and content

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:24.070
can be sequenced, but
mostly in the online space.

00:08:24.070 --> 00:08:30.430
And VPAL Research,
headed by Dustin,

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:34.659
is an organization
that draws on the data

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:36.760
structures from
residential education

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:41.890
and from online education to
help to build tools and build

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:45.850
a research program that
can help us understand

00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:49.240
teaching and learning
improvements more broadly.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:54.010
Out of VPAL Research came
another organization,

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:57.940
DART, Digital Assets
for Reuse and Teaching.

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:00.760
And we think DART could actually
be considered a curriculum

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:03.480
mapping project, which is a
little confusing, because it's

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:05.910
an organization, and it's
part of another organization.

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:08.020
But it's also one of
these curricular mapping

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:10.690
projects, which we'll
say a little bit

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:11.950
more about in a minute.

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:18.547
So HILT's mission is catalyzing
innovation and excellence

00:09:18.547 --> 00:09:21.130
in learning and teaching and,
as I said, largely through grant

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:22.004
making and convening.

