That's actually really
valuable information.

00:17:30.580 --> 00:17:33.310
What are they experiencing as
they are going through what

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:35.129
I want them to experience?

00:17:35.129 --> 00:17:37.420
And we'll talk a little bit
more about nearest neighbor

00:17:37.420 --> 00:17:38.540
in a second.

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:40.660
And you can think
about these things.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:43.330
So this is going to be for
the physics department.

00:17:43.330 --> 00:17:45.130
So we've been working
with them, as well.

00:17:45.130 --> 00:17:46.480
So I'm teaching a class.

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:49.120
There are these other classes
that students are enrolled in.

00:17:49.120 --> 00:17:51.320
You can even see the second
order nearest neighbor.

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:53.320
This is like not your
neighbor, but the neighbor

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:55.330
down the street, right.

00:17:55.330 --> 00:17:58.600
And what classes that
overlap are happening there.

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:01.690
Or what's the sequence of
classes that people are taking?

00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:03.460
What have people
taken before my class?

00:18:03.460 --> 00:18:06.766
And what do people statistically
tend to take afterwards?

00:18:06.766 --> 00:18:08.140
And then, finally,
there's always

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:10.420
questions about, like, are
there trends in enrollment

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:13.880
that we within a department
administratively look at.

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:15.820
And so this is
something that we will

00:18:15.820 --> 00:18:19.260
be rolling out to a whole
range of FAS departments.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:21.490
I'm working quite
closely with Harvard's

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:24.450
institutional research and
our friends over in HUIT

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:25.810
to be able to do.

