This is a little bit of
a moving target, as well.

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:18.660
This is not fixed in stone.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:21.110
It might change in the coming
months and year and whatnot.

00:19:21.110 --> 00:19:24.350
But there are some different
data systems out there.

00:19:24.350 --> 00:19:28.440
We have been working a lot
with the my.Harvard back end.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:30.060
But there are some
others out there.

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:32.390
And one of the
things that we do is

00:19:32.390 --> 00:19:36.020
to try to think about
common underlying things

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:38.360
so that even if people have
different data systems,

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:42.890
we can bring that data together
and have it be meaningful to be

00:19:42.890 --> 00:19:44.780
co-located together.

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:47.720
A final piece that really,
I think, highlights

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:50.240
the opportunities
for merging data

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:52.370
from a whole
variety of systems--

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:54.290
this is the syllabus
exploration tool.

00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:58.040
This is something that is now
available to anyone in FAS.

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:02.330
You can go to a
syllabus.hmdc.harvard.edu,

00:20:02.330 --> 00:20:06.950
and you can search across
most of the syllabi that

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:08.290
are used in the FAS.

00:20:08.290 --> 00:20:08.790
OK.

00:20:08.790 --> 00:20:10.520
So how do we do that?

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:13.520
So what's one thing
that you're supposed

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:17.447
to do if you're an instructor
on your Canvas site?

00:20:17.447 --> 00:20:19.280
What's one thing that
you're supposed to do?

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:21.420
What should you do?

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:23.750
You should post your syllabus.

00:20:23.750 --> 00:20:24.500
OK.

00:20:24.500 --> 00:20:28.610
Now, you are going to do that
in a variety of different ways

00:20:28.610 --> 00:20:31.039
because I can see that data.

00:20:31.039 --> 00:20:33.080
There are particular ways
we prefer you to do it,

00:20:33.080 --> 00:20:35.520
but whatever, we'll
figure it out.

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:37.130
And so what we did is we--

00:20:37.130 --> 00:20:39.380
working very closely
with Dean Mike Smith--

00:20:39.380 --> 00:20:43.340
went out and got
syllabi from across all

00:20:43.340 --> 00:20:46.790
of these different
courses, took those files,

00:20:46.790 --> 00:20:49.190
extracted the text
from them, and then

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:50.930
essentially made it
searchable, right.

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:53.210
So you can go in, and you
can find people's syllabi,

00:20:53.210 --> 00:20:56.480
and actually get the actual
file that was their syllabus.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:21:00.530
And think of the syllabi
as being essentially

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:02.340
like a curated reading list.

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:04.970
So if you're writing
a senior thesis,

00:21:04.970 --> 00:21:06.920
and you're interested
in some topic,

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:09.830
well, one thing you could do is
you could go to Google and type

00:21:09.830 --> 00:21:10.970
in that topic.

00:21:10.970 --> 00:21:13.880
And then, who knows where
you're going, right?

00:21:13.880 --> 00:21:15.920
But why not, if you
could, in a sense,

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:19.190
like Google the inside of some
of the most brilliant people's

00:21:19.190 --> 00:21:20.314
minds in the world.

00:21:20.314 --> 00:21:22.730
And see what they would suggest
reading, given your topic.

00:21:22.730 --> 00:21:24.830
That would be a much
greater opportunity.

00:21:24.830 --> 00:21:27.320
So the syllabus project
took information

00:21:27.320 --> 00:21:29.810
from Canvas, the learning
management system on the one

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:33.650
hand, brought it together
with some other information

00:21:33.650 --> 00:21:38.300
from the operational data
storage system in HUIT,

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:39.920
and put those things together.

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:42.830
And now we have this
as a product for FAS.

00:21:42.830 --> 00:21:44.930
And furthermore, it's
been written in a way

00:21:44.930 --> 00:21:47.512
that we hope some of our
friends from other schools

00:21:47.512 --> 00:21:49.220
would be interested
in joining the party.

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:51.200
So at some point, this
could be something

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:54.920
like syllabus.harvard.edu
and really scale

00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:56.149
across the institution.

00:21:56.149 --> 00:21:58.190
That's a dream right now,
but I'm a jump starter.

