helped the School of
Education get to a place

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:04.490
where, in May, they
voted successfully

00:23:04.490 --> 00:23:08.240
on a curricular reform
for the master's programs

00:23:08.240 --> 00:23:09.540
at the school.

00:23:09.540 --> 00:23:11.600
And I think it
took a lot of work

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:15.710
and a lot of thinking
to get there.

00:23:15.710 --> 00:23:19.820
And I want us to just imagine
some of the challenges here,

00:23:19.820 --> 00:23:23.660
like a master's student
who comes to the Ed School

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:26.840
could choose one of
13 different tracks.

00:23:26.840 --> 00:23:31.540
There are about 700 that
come from master's programs

00:23:31.540 --> 00:23:35.410
and you're just on
campus for one year.

00:23:35.410 --> 00:23:39.740
Now, how do you think
about a professional school

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:44.240
in education and imagine each
of those different tracks

00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:47.360
and educating them to have the
competencies to go out and do

00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:49.520
what they need to do in
a bunch of different ways

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:53.150
in a bunch of different
kinds of professions?

00:23:53.150 --> 00:23:55.100
So at the Ed School, people--

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:58.020
the students, as I
understand it, they come in

00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:02.670
and it's not like undergraduates
coming into a core program

00:24:02.670 --> 00:24:04.900
and learning what it is
that they want to do.

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:06.150
They're professional students.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.340
They have some ideas about
what they want to do.

00:24:08.340 --> 00:24:11.250
But they come from all
different kinds of backgrounds.

00:24:11.250 --> 00:24:14.070
And some people want
to be data scientists,

00:24:14.070 --> 00:24:16.249
and some people want
to be policy makers,

00:24:16.249 --> 00:24:17.790
and some people want
to be educators,

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:19.904
and some people want
to be superintendents.

00:24:19.904 --> 00:24:22.320
And there's different ways
that you might come in and want

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:25.500
to use a master's program.

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:28.380
So part of the
curriculum redesign

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:31.140
was a set of
discussions about what

00:24:31.140 --> 00:24:35.400
are the core competencies
that faculty can agree on

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:38.500
should cross all of these.

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:41.590
But how can we, now,
using technology,

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:44.149
using what we understand
about pedagogy,

00:24:44.149 --> 00:24:46.690
actually think through how to
deliver that in a personalized,

00:24:46.690 --> 00:24:48.810
individualized way
for students who

00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:50.490
come from different
backgrounds and need

00:24:50.490 --> 00:24:52.830
to go into different places.

00:24:52.830 --> 00:24:56.550
So it's a tough set of problems.

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:58.320
And I'm focusing
on it a little bit

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:00.060
because I think it's
a set of problems

00:25:00.060 --> 00:25:02.970
that many of our
schools struggle with,

00:25:02.970 --> 00:25:05.160
many of the professional
schools, in particular.

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:06.576
You have people
who are coming in,

00:25:06.576 --> 00:25:08.470
and all of these
different backgrounds,

00:25:08.470 --> 00:25:10.070
and they need to go out
in these different ways.

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:11.550
But you have to,
as a school, say

00:25:11.550 --> 00:25:13.170
what are these
core competencies,

00:25:13.170 --> 00:25:17.500
and how might we deliver
education flexibly,

00:25:17.500 --> 00:25:22.350
in individualized ways, to
be able to get them through

00:25:22.350 --> 00:25:25.570
and learn from the time
while they're on campus,

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:27.450
which isn't very long.

00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:32.010
So how do we allow
learners flexibility

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:34.440
as they're attaining the same
professional competencies,

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:38.820
leverage technology and data to
support diverse adult learners,

00:25:38.820 --> 00:25:43.320
prepare professionals for an
evolving career in education?

00:25:43.320 --> 00:25:46.450
And the key constituents here
are master's degree students,

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:48.840
faculty, staff, and alumni.

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:55.680
And you can see where
they see this process.

