and department

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:46.170
level learning outcomes.

00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:48.590
So a little bit of
history behind this.

00:32:48.590 --> 00:32:53.030
So Chris Stubbs, who recently
served a term as interim chair

00:32:53.030 --> 00:32:55.449
and previously had been chair
of the physics department,

00:32:55.449 --> 00:32:56.990
has long been
interested in improving

00:32:56.990 --> 00:32:58.790
undergraduate education.

00:32:58.790 --> 00:33:01.780
When he was the
department chair,

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:04.460
he brought Carl Wieman to
campus to talk to faculty

00:33:04.460 --> 00:33:06.807
about creating learning
objectives for their courses

00:33:06.807 --> 00:33:09.140
and helping faculty to try
to define, what do you really

00:33:09.140 --> 00:33:12.440
want them to learn when they
take electricity and magnetism

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:16.220
or quantum mechanics or whatever
that individual course is?

00:33:16.220 --> 00:33:19.679
And Chris, at the time, said,
OK, I'm department chair.

00:33:19.679 --> 00:33:22.220
I can just wave my magic wand
and make everyone make learning

00:33:22.220 --> 00:33:23.840
objectives for their courses.

00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:26.210
And of course, we
know that didn't work.

00:33:26.210 --> 00:33:28.190
[LAUGHING]

00:33:28.190 --> 00:33:32.150
But Chris realized that this
idea of actually defining

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:34.262
learning objectives is
a very powerful notion--

00:33:34.262 --> 00:33:35.720
that you can really
articulate what

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:39.680
it means to learn the content
and skills and concepts

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:41.450
in a course.

00:33:41.450 --> 00:33:43.790
And a few years later, when
Chris was serving a term

00:33:43.790 --> 00:33:45.650
as interim chair
of the department,

00:33:45.650 --> 00:33:49.102
he wondered, is there anything
I can do, one semester as chair,

00:33:49.102 --> 00:33:51.560
that could have a lasting impact
on undergraduate education

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:53.000
in the department?

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:56.240
And he turned to
Louis Deslaurier

00:33:56.240 --> 00:33:59.570
who is Director of Science
Teaching and Learning in FAS,

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:02.150
and also a senior preceptor
in our department.

00:34:02.150 --> 00:34:06.500
And Louis is one of the great
experts in science education,

00:34:06.500 --> 00:34:07.580
here.

00:34:07.580 --> 00:34:09.380
And Louis immediately
said, well,

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:12.110
there is something that
no one else is doing,

00:34:12.110 --> 00:34:14.540
which is actually looking
at the department level

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:16.062
at learning objectives.

00:34:16.062 --> 00:34:18.020
What, as a department,
are we actually teaching

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:19.670
our physics undergraduates?

00:34:19.670 --> 00:34:22.699
And Louis said, no one's doing
this at other institutions

00:34:22.699 --> 00:34:24.870
because they think
it's just too hard.

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:25.370
OK.

00:34:25.370 --> 00:34:26.828
They think that
logistically trying

00:34:26.828 --> 00:34:29.390
to get all of the students
and trying to get faculty

00:34:29.390 --> 00:34:31.639
to agree about what the
department learning objectives

00:34:31.639 --> 00:34:33.679
are-- these will
be too challenging.

00:34:33.679 --> 00:34:35.659
So Chris said, OK, let's do it.

00:34:35.659 --> 00:34:37.130
[LAUGHING]

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:44.360
And so this project was launched
with some specially arranged

00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:46.658
help from HILT. At
the HILT conference

00:34:46.658 --> 00:34:48.199
where-- those of
you who were there--

00:34:48.199 --> 00:34:52.370
remember that Chris was
presented as a guinea pig,

00:34:52.370 --> 00:34:55.340
if you will, with an opportunity
for the entire HILT conference

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:57.380
to weigh in on what Chris
ought to do in his one

00:34:57.380 --> 00:35:01.161
semester as interim chair to
improve teaching and learning

00:35:01.161 --> 00:35:01.910
in the department.

00:35:01.910 --> 00:35:05.360
And one of the options was
create a departmental level

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:07.989
assessment to assess teaching
and learning in the department.

00:35:07.989 --> 00:35:10.280
And Lo and behold, that was
one of the recommendations.

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:13.449
So with that
ringing endorsement,

00:35:13.449 --> 00:35:15.740
one of the curriculum mapping
projects that was started

00:35:15.740 --> 00:35:17.600
was this very project.

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:19.760
So we wanted to
know, how do we know

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:21.680
if the department, as
a whole, is actually

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:23.732
successful in teaching
the concepts and skills

00:35:23.732 --> 00:35:25.940
that we think are important
for undergraduate success

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:30.260
in physics and future success
as they go into their careers,

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:31.580
or graduate schools?

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:33.050
How do we actually
engage faculty

00:35:33.050 --> 00:35:35.216
in thinking about departmental
level learning goals?

00:35:35.216 --> 00:35:38.850
As you can imagine, that
can be a contentious issue.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:40.767
And how do we increase
our students' awareness

00:35:40.767 --> 00:35:42.683
about what they know and
what they don't know?

00:35:42.683 --> 00:35:45.290
So we're looking here both at
the undergraduate concentrators

00:35:45.290 --> 00:35:48.590
and at the faculty to try
to understand this better.

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:51.080
So our goals by
June of next year

00:35:51.080 --> 00:35:53.027
is that we'll have, we
hope, a system in place

00:35:53.027 --> 00:35:54.860
where all of our
undergraduate concentrators

00:35:54.860 --> 00:35:56.270
are assessed twice.

00:35:56.270 --> 00:35:58.520
First around of the end of
their second year and again

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:00.110
in their fourth year.

00:36:00.110 --> 00:36:03.140
That we have student level
and departmental level

00:36:03.140 --> 00:36:05.870
interventions in response
to these results and that

00:36:05.870 --> 00:36:09.260
we can actually validate
the assessment itself.

00:36:09.260 --> 00:36:11.790
This is a little snapshot
of part of the assessment,

