00:36:29.930 --> 00:36:32.180
we can actually
target those reforms

00:36:32.180 --> 00:36:34.850
at places where we know
that we need to focus,

00:36:34.850 --> 00:36:36.260
in terms of outcomes.

00:36:36.260 --> 00:36:38.450
And then we can actually
assess those changes

00:36:38.450 --> 00:36:39.835
on a department level.

00:36:39.835 --> 00:36:41.960
And finally, we hope that
our students can actually

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:43.804
be more confident
and can articulate

00:36:43.804 --> 00:36:45.470
what the skills are
that they've learned

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:47.480
as undergraduate
concentrators in physics.

00:36:47.480 --> 00:36:50.030
And now, I will turn
this over to Louis,

00:36:50.030 --> 00:36:53.450
who understands this all
much more deeply than I do,

00:36:53.450 --> 00:36:55.724
to explain a little bit
more about the details

00:36:55.724 --> 00:36:56.390
of this project.

00:37:01.080 --> 00:37:01.580
OK.

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:04.000
So a little bit about
the design here.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:07.800
So first, the test is made up of
a broad range of topics, right.

00:37:07.800 --> 00:37:09.960
We want to make sure that
faculty and students feel

00:37:09.960 --> 00:37:12.150
like it's quite
representative of what

00:37:12.150 --> 00:37:16.440
it means to be a physicist, by
the end of your fourth year.

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:19.830
So I made sure to see as many
colleagues and department

00:37:19.830 --> 00:37:21.840
as possible to get their input.

00:37:21.840 --> 00:37:23.760
And I asked them,
what do you think

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:26.310
are the most important skills,
most important concepts,

00:37:26.310 --> 00:37:29.670
that your students should
master by the time they get out

00:37:29.670 --> 00:37:30.930
of the program?

00:37:30.930 --> 00:37:33.520
And I got a lot of
feedback, obviously.

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:35.310
But one thing that was common--

00:37:35.310 --> 00:37:38.160
feedback that was
common to everyone

00:37:38.160 --> 00:37:44.100
was about they wanted to make
sure that this assessment did

00:37:44.100 --> 00:37:47.220
not look just like a final exam
at the end of a course, which

00:37:47.220 --> 00:37:51.030
in physics often times involve
end of the chapter, end

00:37:51.030 --> 00:37:52.100
of the textbook problems.

00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:54.340
So they didn't want the
exam to look like that.

00:37:54.340 --> 00:37:58.140
And that's why if you
look at the assessment,

00:37:58.140 --> 00:38:00.985
we have some practical lab
physics questions on there.

00:38:00.985 --> 00:38:02.610
We have even some
open-ended questions.

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:06.030
So it really does
feel quite different.

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:10.110
But most importantly, I wanted
to make sure that it only

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:11.842
had conceptual questions.

00:38:11.842 --> 00:38:13.800
And it's well known, now,
in science education,

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:18.360
that the retention of concepts
is quite robust over time

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:21.390
when you compare that
to retention of facts--

00:38:21.390 --> 00:38:24.176
facts like procedures,
steps that you

00:38:24.176 --> 00:38:25.800
need to solve an
equation or something.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:29.010
That's just forgotten almost in
that the same rate as a phone

00:38:29.010 --> 00:38:30.960
number or someone's name, right.

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:33.750
In fact, several years
ago, we published something

00:38:33.750 --> 00:38:39.240
where we looked at how students
retain quantum mechanics

00:38:39.240 --> 00:38:39.840
concepts.

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:42.270
At the end of their first
quantum mechanics course,

00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:44.010
students were given
a test of learning.

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:46.740
And the test of
learning comprised

00:38:46.740 --> 00:38:50.090
deeply conceptual questions
as well as procedures.

00:38:50.090 --> 00:38:50.684
Right.

00:38:50.684 --> 00:38:52.350
So a year and a half
later, we gave them

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:54.141
the same test of
learning, and we made sure

00:38:54.141 --> 00:38:57.720
that they had no exposure to
quantum mechanics in between.

00:38:57.720 --> 00:39:01.210
And interestingly, the concept
was retained almost at 100%.

00:39:01.210 --> 00:39:01.710
OK.

00:39:01.710 --> 00:39:04.290
The deeply conceptual
ideas, but the facts,

00:39:04.290 --> 00:39:05.880
procedures, not
surprisingly, they

00:39:05.880 --> 00:39:08.592
had decayed almost to
zero-- to noise level.

00:39:08.592 --> 00:39:10.050
So that's why I
wanted to make sure

00:39:10.050 --> 00:39:13.860
that the feedback that
this test would give us,

00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:16.670
faculty and students,
was meaningful.

00:39:16.670 --> 00:39:19.170
So in fact, you'll see when I
talk about student interviews,

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:23.520
here, not a single student
said, oh, I learned this before,

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:27.300
but I think I did not answer
it correctly because I forgot.

00:39:27.300 --> 00:39:29.880
Because people know
intuitively these questions.

00:39:29.880 --> 00:39:32.430
If you just don't know how
to answer them a year later,

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:34.680
that's because you didn't
learn it in the first place.

00:39:34.680 --> 00:39:37.230
So that's a very important
part of the design.

00:39:37.230 --> 00:39:39.660
So I tried to use as many
validated questions as

00:39:39.660 --> 00:39:40.830
possible.

00:39:40.830 --> 00:39:42.820
I called my colleagues
at other universities,

00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:45.570
but we can only use a few.

00:39:45.570 --> 00:39:49.990
So this assessment will have
to be validated this year.

00:39:49.990 --> 00:39:51.960
So let's talk about
results a little bit.

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:55.660
Students did not perform
as well as they hoped.

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:59.190
So with an average of
46%, and the distribution

00:39:59.190 --> 00:40:00.370
was pretty wide.

00:40:00.370 --> 00:40:05.310
So now, you should know, if
you ask is this test too hard?

00:40:05.310 --> 00:40:07.500
Well, I started to give
it to graduate students,

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:11.010
so they score a lot higher,
but still not that great.

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:12.900
Much worse than they would like.

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:16.890
And I just got the green light,
I think, in the last faculty

00:40:16.890 --> 00:40:19.650
meeting that we had, to start
giving it to my colleagues.

00:40:19.650 --> 00:40:23.570
[LAUGHING]

00:40:25.540 --> 00:40:30.060
Anyway, it'll be
anonymous, right?

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:32.280
I'll say, I'm the only
one that has the key.

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:34.125
So I'll be able to get
favors from people.

00:40:34.125 --> 00:40:36.190
[LAUGHING]

00:40:36.190 --> 00:40:39.690
So here's what's really
interesting, here, everyone--

00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:42.720
no exception-- expected
to get an A on this test,

00:40:42.720 --> 00:40:44.230
and they were all
very disappointed.

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:45.810
So that's a bit of
a downer, right?

00:40:45.810 --> 00:40:47.234
Very disappointed, in fact.

00:40:47.234 --> 00:40:48.900
To the point where I
was quite concerned

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:51.250
with a few first students.

00:40:51.250 --> 00:40:53.170
But I interviewed every student.

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:55.050
So I made them one-on-one.

00:40:55.050 --> 00:40:57.840
And part of the script at the
beginning for the interview

00:40:57.840 --> 00:41:00.307
was about their perception
of fairness for the test.

00:41:00.307 --> 00:41:02.265
I asked them, is the test
fair in your opinion?

00:41:02.265 --> 00:41:04.482
And I just let them talk.

00:41:04.482 --> 00:41:06.690
Then, after that, I provide
them with a definition we

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:08.150
can both agree on for fairness.

00:41:08.150 --> 00:41:10.320
The definition I gave
them is that I said,

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:14.340
let's imagine that for example
the questions on quantum

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:15.750
mechanics for this test--

00:41:15.750 --> 00:41:18.350
let's say that you had
been asked those questions

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:21.239
at the end of your course where
you learned quantum mechanics.

00:41:21.239 --> 00:41:23.280
Would it be fair for the
instructor in the course

00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:26.650
to expect you to get all
these questions right?

00:41:26.650 --> 00:41:29.090
And without exception,
students said, yes, absolutely.

00:41:29.090 --> 00:41:31.080
At the end of a course
in quantum mechanics,

00:41:31.080 --> 00:41:33.660
I should get those quantum
mechanics questions right.

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:35.460
So they did feel like
the test was fair.

00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:38.290
So it was very
disappointed to them.

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:40.110
But on the upside,
students really

00:41:40.110 --> 00:41:42.270
did appreciate the feedback.

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:46.530
I mean, many of them went out of
their ways to thank me, to say,

00:41:46.530 --> 00:41:48.330
oh, I'm so glad that
the department is

00:41:48.330 --> 00:41:50.340
spending a lot of
time and energy

00:41:50.340 --> 00:41:52.650
to give me additional feedback.

00:41:52.650 --> 00:41:56.712
And many of them asked, OK,
what can I do practically now?

00:41:56.712 --> 00:41:58.920
These are students that are
about to graduate, right,

00:41:58.920 --> 00:41:59.610
in fourth years.

00:41:59.610 --> 00:42:03.360
They said, only got a few months
before I go to graduate school.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:04.130
What can I do?

00:42:04.130 --> 00:42:05.270
Give me some advice.

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:08.300
So it's pretty clear that we
can't just give this assessment

00:42:08.300 --> 00:42:09.594
and leave it at that.

00:42:09.594 --> 00:42:11.510
We need to provide
students with opportunities

00:42:11.510 --> 00:42:14.490
to bridge some of the gaps.

00:42:14.490 --> 00:42:18.020
So another upside is that
the assessment can definitely

00:42:18.020 --> 00:42:22.130
help students improve their
self-awareness as they progress

00:42:22.130 --> 00:42:23.244
through the program.

00:42:23.244 --> 00:42:24.660
And that's in
addition, of course,

00:42:24.660 --> 00:42:29.480
to helping us improve teaching
and learning in our department.

00:42:29.480 --> 00:42:31.730
So something that's
very interesting, here,

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:34.900
as part of the
interviews, is I asked

00:42:34.900 --> 00:42:38.090
students, what is it that
made you think that you should

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:39.930
have gotten an A on this test?

00:42:39.930 --> 00:42:43.850
And you know, not all of
them, but almost all of them,

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:45.440
they talk about their grades.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:46.790
They said, well, it's too bad.

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:50.210
The only feedback that I get
from the program are my grades.

00:42:50.210 --> 00:42:51.870
And I did pretty
good in my classes.

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:54.161
So that's why I would have
assumed that I would do well

00:42:54.161 --> 00:42:55.260
on something like that.

00:42:55.260 --> 00:42:59.240
So that was the source of their
disappointment, basically.

00:42:59.240 --> 00:43:02.180
So as Logan mentioned,
when you think

00:43:02.180 --> 00:43:04.610
about this, that's a pretty
backward way to design things,

00:43:04.610 --> 00:43:05.110
right?

00:43:05.110 --> 00:43:07.124
You're supposed to do
learning outcomes first,

00:43:07.124 --> 00:43:08.540
and then from that
you're supposed

00:43:08.540 --> 00:43:10.160
to build an assessment.

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:12.770
But we know it, practically,
just doesn't work that way.

00:43:12.770 --> 00:43:15.320
Well, you should have seen
this in the faculty meeting--

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:16.370
the last one that we had.

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:18.440
I mean, people were
really engaged, right.

00:43:18.440 --> 00:43:22.580
So that might be a good way
to trick faculty into starting

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:25.590
to talk about these things.

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:28.250
So the next steps here for
this coming year is, of course,

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:32.680
we need to design follow up
opportunities for students--

00:43:32.680 --> 00:43:34.040
some seminar type courses.

00:43:34.040 --> 00:43:38.640
We're bouncing ideas--
what we should do.

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:40.700
We need to revise and
validate the assessment.

00:43:40.700 --> 00:43:43.187
And that will involve
a lot of interviews.

00:43:43.187 --> 00:43:45.770
So I want to make sure that we
make this available to everyone

00:43:45.770 --> 00:43:48.620
around the world, so they
can use this instrument.

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:51.860
And Karen Pearce, from
Institutional Research,

00:43:51.860 --> 00:43:55.580
is already helping us, now,
with looking at correlations

00:43:55.580 --> 00:43:56.960
with other institutional data.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:44:01.070
For example, what courses
did students take?

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:02.195
What grades did they take?

00:44:02.195 --> 00:44:06.650
And does that inform their
performance on this test?

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:08.589
And then, finally,
and not the least,

00:44:08.589 --> 00:44:10.880
is that we need to develop
sustainable way to give that

00:44:10.880 --> 00:44:11.820
to students.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:14.330
So we want to give it at
the end of second year

00:44:14.330 --> 00:44:15.830
and at the end of fourth year.

00:44:15.830 --> 00:44:18.080
So students did
mention in interviews,

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:19.970
I wish I would have
had something like this

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:22.070
two years ago, because
I would have been

00:44:22.070 --> 00:44:23.660
able to make some corrections.

00:44:23.660 --> 00:44:24.830
It's too bad.

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:27.620
So giving it at the end of
second year-- that's easy

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:29.160
I would think not
just in physics,

00:44:29.160 --> 00:44:32.990
but in most departments because
we have core courses, right.

00:44:32.990 --> 00:44:36.020
Like this fall semester, I'm
teaching quantum mechanics

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:38.432
and every students have to
go through quantum mechanics.

00:44:38.432 --> 00:44:39.890
So I'm going to
give it to students

00:44:39.890 --> 00:44:41.090
at the end of the course.

00:44:41.090 --> 00:44:42.017
That's easy.

00:44:42.017 --> 00:44:44.600
But at the end of fourth year,
though, that's a serious issue.

00:44:44.600 --> 00:44:48.440
This semester was really hard
to communicate with each student

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:52.985
individually, and schedule
time, and so forth.

00:44:52.985 --> 00:44:56.817
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:00.180 --> 00:45:01.920
Can you imagine a
world where that was

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:04.031
happening in every department?

00:45:04.031 --> 00:45:04.530
All right.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:09.330
So we're going to move on
to a different category.

00:45:09.330 --> 00:45:12.790
And we're going to
go in this order.

00:45:12.790 --> 00:45:14.700
And then at the end,
we're going to have

00:45:14.700 --> 00:45:19.350
a little more depth about the
social innovation project.

00:45:19.350 --> 00:45:22.770
So I love this project.

00:45:22.770 --> 00:45:25.500
It's the project that
when everyone says to me,

00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:26.820
what is curriculum mapping?

00:45:26.820 --> 00:45:32.090
It's the one that I bring up
because it's just so clear.

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:34.970
Like, if you said,
across the university,

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:36.720
what are all of the
courses, all the ways,

00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:38.430
that ethics is being taught?

00:45:38.430 --> 00:45:41.700
It's probably taught in
every Harvard School.

00:45:41.700 --> 00:45:46.110
How do we know where
the ethics courses are?

00:45:46.110 --> 00:45:50.250
So the team-- which
you can see here--

00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:52.680
Danielle Allen couldn't be here.

00:45:52.680 --> 00:45:58.170
Jess Miner, Michael
Blauw, David Comer

00:45:58.170 --> 00:46:02.190
Kidd they have been
working really hard.

00:46:02.190 --> 00:46:05.940
And as I understand it, you
took inductive and deductive

00:46:05.940 --> 00:46:11.340
approaches, both, to narrowing
in on the range of many words

00:46:11.340 --> 00:46:14.340
that could be related
to ethics instruction.

00:46:14.340 --> 00:46:17.839
And then you used that to
develop a weighted algorithm.

00:46:17.839 --> 00:46:19.380
And then used that
weighted algorithm

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:21.900
to search all of the
syllabi, and then

00:46:21.900 --> 00:46:29.010
to identify courses, survey
instructors, get their teaching

00:46:29.010 --> 00:46:31.140
learning materials,
that then become

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:36.570
additional sources of data to
draw out the implicit learning

00:46:36.570 --> 00:46:38.280
theories around ethics.

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:41.790
And to begin to think about
not just which courses,

00:46:41.790 --> 00:46:45.150
but the pedagogical
approaches to teaching ethics.

00:46:45.150 --> 00:46:49.170
And how to develop a community,
here, around those issues.

00:46:49.170 --> 00:46:51.450
And then broaden that
community, outside of Harvard,

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:53.400
and think about
ethics instruction

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:57.510
out there in the world
and in other institutions.

00:46:57.510 --> 00:47:02.780
So key constituents--
undergraduate and professional

00:47:02.780 --> 00:47:05.124
students, faculty instructors,
and administrators.

00:47:05.124 --> 00:47:06.290
That's the whole university.

00:47:06.290 --> 00:47:07.910
[LAUGHING]

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:10.850
I think you could add alumni.

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:17.780
And I do think it does
have that applicability.

00:47:17.780 --> 00:47:20.290
So look at this visual.

00:47:20.290 --> 00:47:23.180
How many courses
were identified?

00:47:23.180 --> 00:47:26.260
That's a lot of courses.

00:47:26.260 --> 00:47:30.400
Then there is how many
were selected out of that,

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:32.410
and unique instructors.

00:47:32.410 --> 00:47:34.840
And look at how many
survey responses they got.

00:47:34.840 --> 00:47:39.100
This is already a community.

00:47:39.100 --> 00:47:43.060
By next year, the goal is to
do another round of faculty

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:45.760
surveys, refine and
administer the pre-

00:47:45.760 --> 00:47:47.830
and post-semester
student surveys--

00:47:47.830 --> 00:47:50.140
so now learning from students--

00:47:50.140 --> 00:47:54.040
and test and transfer the
methodology to other campuses.

00:47:54.040 --> 00:47:57.220
And hopes for curriculum
mapping at Harvard--

00:47:57.220 --> 00:48:00.460
build student-friendly tools
for identifying ethics courses

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:02.630
and learning opportunities.

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:05.194
What do student-friendly
tools look like?

00:48:05.194 --> 00:48:06.610
We'll be getting
to that because I

00:48:06.610 --> 00:48:09.430
think Jeffrey and others
in the curricle project

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:13.480
are also thinking about
student-friendly tools.

00:48:13.480 --> 00:48:17.620
Identify strengths and gaps in
ethics education at Harvard,

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:20.500
promote discussion
and collaboration.

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:25.570
Similarly, Subu,
a faculty member

00:48:25.570 --> 00:48:28.900
in the School of Public Health,
had another kind of question

00:48:28.900 --> 00:48:34.060
that was crossing instruction
all across Harvard,

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:37.280
who's teaching applied
quantitative methods?

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:40.120
What are the applied statistics
courses that are being taught?

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:42.190
In social sciences,
by non-statisticians,

00:48:42.190 --> 00:48:43.660
how did these courses compare?

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:47.650
How do students move through
the system to take courses

00:48:47.650 --> 00:48:48.700
in applied statistics?

00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:50.260
And people do move.

00:48:50.260 --> 00:48:52.630
They don't just stick
in their school.

00:48:52.630 --> 00:48:54.850
They move to other
schools to try

00:48:54.850 --> 00:48:58.180
to get the methodological
training that they

00:48:58.180 --> 00:48:59.500
feel that they need.

00:48:59.500 --> 00:49:02.800
Graduate students are the
key constituency, here,

00:49:02.800 --> 00:49:05.470
and then faculty.

00:49:05.470 --> 00:49:07.780
By next year, have
a web resource

00:49:07.780 --> 00:49:11.410
to facilitate optimal course
selection for students,

00:49:11.410 --> 00:49:16.090
a synthesis-based deep dive of
what's being taught at Harvard,

00:49:16.090 --> 00:49:19.480
with an aim to develop a
taxonomy of these courses.

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:20.920
That's a big goal.

00:49:20.920 --> 00:49:22.850
It should be an interesting one.

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:25.990
And again, it will be drawing
on the data sources of syllabi

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:27.400
and course materials.

00:49:29.980 --> 00:49:35.560
Subu or Judy might remember,
as we identified these courses,

00:49:35.560 --> 00:49:37.820
reached out to
faculty, and said, hey,

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:39.070
could you send us our syllabi?

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:40.900
Because we couldn't
use syllabus tool

00:49:40.900 --> 00:49:44.260
because it was not
just in the FAS.

00:49:44.260 --> 00:49:47.290
Within an hour, you had
like hundreds of people,

00:49:47.290 --> 00:49:49.230
or a lot of people writing.

00:49:49.230 --> 00:49:51.490
There is a hunger
among the faculty

00:49:51.490 --> 00:49:54.400
to be able to share their
resources with one another

00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:57.190
and to build this
kind of community.

00:49:57.190 --> 00:50:01.780
So one of the goals is just
making this meaningful faculty

00:50:01.780 --> 00:50:04.780
connections and then providing
more course selection

00:50:04.780 --> 00:50:06.860
support to students.

00:50:06.860 --> 00:50:08.500
If you look at this
visual, you can

00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:11.650
see the percentage of the
applied quantitative methods

00:50:11.650 --> 00:50:15.290
by school, but we don't know
if this picture is accurate.

00:50:15.290 --> 00:50:16.490
We really don't know.

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:18.280
I think this is a first stab.

00:50:18.280 --> 00:50:21.280
And then we have to iterate
and learn to what degree this

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:22.390
might change over time.

00:50:25.420 --> 00:50:33.440
So curricle is this amazing
intellectual project.

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:36.550
And when I first heard about
it, my jaw almost dropped.

00:50:36.550 --> 00:50:40.000
I really couldn't believe
that this ambitious effort

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.190
was underway.

00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:47.650
We have Jeffrey, Matthew Battles
couldn't be here, Sebastian, we

00:50:47.650 --> 00:50:54.730
have Jessica, Kim,
here, from the team.

00:50:54.730 --> 00:50:58.190
And you can see here, we've
got these two different--

00:50:58.190 --> 00:51:03.400
they're both doing user testing
and still collecting data.

00:51:03.400 --> 00:51:06.020
As I have thought
about this project,

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:07.970
there's two parts of it.

00:51:07.970 --> 00:51:12.220
One is building a
curiosity-driven search

00:51:12.220 --> 00:51:13.660
tool for students.

00:51:13.660 --> 00:51:17.680
And the other is drawing
on really interesting

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:24.160
archival data about the
intellectual, curricular story

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:25.720
of Harvard over time.

00:51:25.720 --> 00:51:28.990
I mean, going back the
hundreds of years of the things

00:51:28.990 --> 00:51:34.360
that have been taught
at Harvard, to say,

00:51:34.360 --> 00:51:38.170
how has Dante's
Inferno been taught

00:51:38.170 --> 00:51:40.090
throughout Harvard's history?

00:51:40.090 --> 00:51:44.380
And to develop these kind
of stories of a student's

00:51:44.380 --> 00:51:47.920
progression, while
they were here,

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:51.190
that might get students to
think in different kinds of ways

00:51:51.190 --> 00:51:54.910
than they usually do about
their own progression and path

00:51:54.910 --> 00:51:57.170
through the curriculum.

00:51:57.170 --> 00:52:01.420
So I think it's an ambitious
project because there's

00:52:01.420 --> 00:52:05.620
a lot of data that might not
be digitized and easily put

00:52:05.620 --> 00:52:09.970
into a format where you could
do that kind of deep work.

00:52:09.970 --> 00:52:12.700
At the same time, it really
relates to a lot of the tools

00:52:12.700 --> 00:52:14.330
that Dustin has been building.

00:52:14.330 --> 00:52:16.975
And as we, in a more
