00:56:14.440 --> 00:56:15.540
So hi, I'm Brittany Butler.

00:56:15.540 --> 00:56:17.664
I'm the Executive Director
of the Social Innovation

00:56:17.664 --> 00:56:20.860
and Change Initiative, which is
a relatively new initiative--

00:56:20.860 --> 00:56:22.870
almost two years old
at the Kennedy School,

00:56:22.870 --> 00:56:24.640
and an adjunct lecturer there.

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:29.260
And I'm representing
our team, the SICI team,

00:56:29.260 --> 00:56:31.240
as well as my colleague,
Julie Battilana,

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:34.900
who's a professor
at both HBS and HKS.

00:56:34.900 --> 00:56:38.740
So I have to say,
we're maybe the team

00:56:38.740 --> 00:56:40.300
that joined this
group the latest,

00:56:40.300 --> 00:56:41.980
and thus got to
benefit on riding

00:56:41.980 --> 00:56:44.860
the coattails of the ethics
group, of the search tool,

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:47.440
of the fact that there
will very soon now

00:56:47.440 --> 00:56:51.164
be this syllabus search
tool, because that's

00:56:51.164 --> 00:56:52.080
sort of our next step.

00:56:52.080 --> 00:56:55.780
And so thank you actually
to HILT for involving us.

00:56:55.780 --> 00:56:57.340
We started out--
also, the mission

00:56:57.340 --> 00:56:59.715
of the Social Innovation Change
Initiative at the Kennedy

00:56:59.715 --> 00:57:01.390
School is to generate
new knowledge

00:57:01.390 --> 00:57:03.280
and also to shape the
practice of innovation

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:04.180
with a social intent.

00:57:04.180 --> 00:57:06.490
So not innovation to
make a profit, not

00:57:06.490 --> 00:57:08.710
innovation for its
own sake, but to solve

00:57:08.710 --> 00:57:10.090
a specific social problem.

00:57:10.090 --> 00:57:13.630
And we entered into
this work essentially

00:57:13.630 --> 00:57:15.640
because anecdotally
the student demand

00:57:15.640 --> 00:57:17.920
was just like blasting up.

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:20.410
So our team was immediately
overwhelmed by the number

00:57:20.410 --> 00:57:23.590
of students coming in and asking
for advice about which courses

00:57:23.590 --> 00:57:27.490
they should take, asking about
the i-lab, asking about HIVE,

00:57:27.490 --> 00:57:29.532
asking about all the
competitions on campus

00:57:29.532 --> 00:57:31.490
and how they should be
navigating those things.

00:57:31.490 --> 00:57:32.650
So this is really--

00:57:32.650 --> 00:57:35.650
we entered with a set of
questions about the curricula,

00:57:35.650 --> 00:57:37.840
but also a set of
questions about

00:57:37.840 --> 00:57:40.780
extracurricular activities,
and how those overlap.

00:57:40.780 --> 00:57:42.864
And the thing about social
innovation, unlike many

00:57:42.864 --> 00:57:44.696
of the things that have
been described here,

00:57:44.696 --> 00:57:46.570
but I think this is an
increasing trend also

00:57:46.570 --> 00:57:49.990
in Higher Ed is it's not
actually a discipline.

00:57:49.990 --> 00:57:54.530
It's-- at best, it's a phenomena
inside of certain disciplines,

00:57:54.530 --> 00:57:58.510
and yet year after year, the
interest from students keeps

00:57:58.510 --> 00:57:59.180
rising.

00:57:59.180 --> 00:58:01.810
And as we talk to students
about what they want

00:58:01.810 --> 00:58:04.160
and how they want to make
a difference in the world,

00:58:04.160 --> 00:58:06.010
they say look there's this
specific social problem I care

00:58:06.010 --> 00:58:07.774
about, and what's the
scope and sequence

00:58:07.774 --> 00:58:09.190
that I should be
thinking through,

00:58:09.190 --> 00:58:11.480
as I prepare myself to
go out there and do this.

00:58:11.480 --> 00:58:14.410
And so we had terrible
answers for them.

00:58:14.410 --> 00:58:16.330
And so-- like very basic level.

00:58:16.330 --> 00:58:18.190
We just wanted to know--

00:58:18.190 --> 00:58:18.970
is this the thing?

00:58:18.970 --> 00:58:19.470
Yeah.

00:58:19.470 --> 00:58:21.380
What courses are being taught?

00:58:21.380 --> 00:58:25.270
What out of class innovation
experiences are offered?

00:58:25.270 --> 00:58:28.840
And how do the perceptions
and experiences and demand

00:58:28.840 --> 00:58:30.790
from the students
and external actors

00:58:30.790 --> 00:58:33.820
about what's available
actually compare to the supply?

00:58:33.820 --> 00:58:36.380
I mean, we just didn't
know anything about this.

00:58:36.380 --> 00:58:38.560
And so we are very
much in this stage

00:58:38.560 --> 00:58:42.500
and looking to go deeper soon.

00:58:42.500 --> 00:58:44.390
So again, this is
where we started.

00:58:44.390 --> 00:58:46.690
So there was a
report done in 2013

00:58:46.690 --> 00:58:50.860
that gave us some
indication that 36%

00:58:50.860 --> 00:58:54.730
of cross registration positions
across all the school--

00:58:54.730 --> 00:58:56.800
so this is like a student
making an extra effort

00:58:56.800 --> 00:59:00.010
to go into another school
because they perceive

00:59:00.010 --> 00:59:02.080
that there's something
at another school that

00:59:02.080 --> 00:59:03.490
isn't available in their own.

00:59:03.490 --> 00:59:05.949
30% of those fall
into this category.

00:59:05.949 --> 00:59:07.990
And many of the students
who made those petitions

00:59:07.990 --> 00:59:09.310
were denied.

00:59:09.310 --> 00:59:11.560
So we know there's
interest, just

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:13.660
locally, again, the
anecdotes were there.

00:59:13.660 --> 00:59:16.590
And then on the supply
side, I mean, very spotty--

00:59:16.590 --> 00:59:18.175
but the challenge
for us, also, was it

00:59:18.175 --> 00:59:19.550
was difficult to
answer questions

00:59:19.550 --> 00:59:20.592
for prospective students.

00:59:20.592 --> 00:59:22.841
And at the Kennedy School,
and at the Business School,

00:59:22.841 --> 00:59:24.490
in particular, we
were feeling the pain

00:59:24.490 --> 00:59:27.073
of actually losing perspective
students because even though we

00:59:27.073 --> 00:59:29.320
had this intuition
that, as a whole,

00:59:29.320 --> 00:59:31.720
Harvard University offers
an incredible amount

00:59:31.720 --> 00:59:34.270
on this front, we weren't
able to represent that well.

00:59:34.270 --> 00:59:36.100
And that was scaring us.

00:59:36.100 --> 00:59:37.600
And then yet at
the same time, you

00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:40.036
know the students who were
pursuing this stuff would say,

00:59:40.036 --> 00:59:42.160
like, I've already taken--
sort of that first quote

00:59:42.160 --> 00:59:43.234
that you started with.

00:59:43.234 --> 00:59:45.400
There is a lot of overlap
between these two classes,

00:59:45.400 --> 00:59:46.780
and I really wish someone
could have given me

00:59:46.780 --> 00:59:47.696
a heads up about that.

00:59:47.696 --> 00:59:50.809
Because I don't feel like
I'm optimizing my time here.

00:59:50.809 --> 00:59:51.850
So that's how we started.

00:59:51.850 --> 00:59:54.340
But as we move forward,
some additional questions

00:59:54.340 --> 00:59:56.570
surfaced that, again, I
think are important as folks

00:59:56.570 --> 00:59:59.650
particularly think about
multi-disciplinary initiatives

00:59:59.650 --> 01:00:03.400
or initiatives that aren't
clearly in a discipline,

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:05.210
but where the student
demand is high,

01:00:05.210 --> 01:00:10.060
which is what is Harvard's
responsibility to get clear

01:00:10.060 --> 01:00:12.230
about this stuff, given
that social innovation,

01:00:12.230 --> 01:00:15.470
social change aren't traditional
academic disciplines.

01:00:15.470 --> 01:00:17.650
And that's an open
question, but it's something

01:00:17.650 --> 01:00:21.275
that, increasingly, every year
feels like we need to answer.

01:00:21.275 --> 01:00:22.900
And what can and
should be accomplished

01:00:22.900 --> 01:00:25.090
through the curricular
versus the co-curricular?

01:00:25.090 --> 01:00:27.550
So the Social Innovation
and Change Initiative

01:00:27.550 --> 01:00:29.020
actually runs a
fellowship program.

01:00:29.020 --> 01:00:32.440
It's a co-curricular program for
15 select students every year

01:00:32.440 --> 01:00:35.199
who are working on advancing
a project that they plan

01:00:35.199 --> 01:00:36.490
to continue when they graduate.

01:00:36.490 --> 01:00:39.670
They can get up to $30,000
to advance those projects

01:00:39.670 --> 01:00:40.600
when they finish.

01:00:40.600 --> 01:00:43.120
But is that the only
experience that they should

01:00:43.120 --> 01:00:45.124
be getting here in the school?

01:00:45.124 --> 01:00:46.540
And how does that
relate to what's

01:00:46.540 --> 01:00:47.570
happening in the classroom?

01:00:47.570 --> 01:00:48.850
So very much along
the lines of what's

01:00:48.850 --> 01:00:51.607
going on with the research stuff
and how much is that shaping

01:00:51.607 --> 01:00:52.690
students' experience here?

01:00:52.690 --> 01:00:54.709
It's something we want
to understand better.

01:00:54.709 --> 01:00:56.500
And then what opportunities
are we missing?

01:00:56.500 --> 01:00:59.083
And it just seems like there's
a lot of low-hanging fruit that

01:00:59.083 --> 01:01:00.100
we don't have--

01:01:00.100 --> 01:01:01.780
we don't really
understand again.

01:01:01.780 --> 01:01:03.940
So this is just a
quick sense of how

01:01:03.940 --> 01:01:07.720
we approached putting our
arms around this space

01:01:07.720 --> 01:01:10.570
and even just defining
what we're talking about.

